# Append to ~/.ssh/config, ABOVE the `Host *` block — ssh takes the FIRST value it sees for
# each keyword, so a global `StrictHostKeyChecking ask` further up wins and turns an image
# rebuild into a prompt in the middle of a deploy.
#
# The tooling (deploy.sh, preview.py, device-sweep.py, cssdiff.py) reaches the dev box by
# ssh AND by http at the SAME address: it derives the browser's base URL from
# `ssh -G <host>` (`http://<hostname>`). That is why these point at the container's bridge
# address and not at a published localhost port — a port mapping cannot carry the http
# side of that. Windows-side browsing is what the published ports are for
# (http://localhost:8025 and :8024); see docker/compose.yml.
#
# `router2512` is the DEFAULT every tool falls back to. `router` is deliberately NOT one of
# these — it names the physical box, which is a different question (real radio, real flash,
# real reboot).

Host router2512
    HostName 172.31.0.2
    User root
    # A dev container is recreated often. Its host key is baked into the image (see the
    # Dockerfile) so it survives a `compose up`, but it does change on every rebuild —
    # and the global `Host *` block here sets StrictHostKeyChecking ask, which turns that
    # into a prompt in the middle of a deploy.
    StrictHostKeyChecking no
    UserKnownHostsFile /dev/null
    LogLevel ERROR

Host router2410
    HostName 172.31.0.3
    User root
    StrictHostKeyChecking no
    UserKnownHostsFile /dev/null
    LogLevel ERROR
